Chapter Forty-Eight.	CHAPTER FORTY-EIGHT.	0.85255253
On Cauterizing Numbness: When a limb becomes numb and is treated with medications, ointments, and bandages but does not heal, cauterize the numb limb itself with cauterizations according to what the size of the limb, large or small, requires.  And let your cauterization penetrate slightly into the thickness of the skin.	On cauterization for numbness. When some limb is affected with numbness and it is treated with drugs and ointments and plasters, but is not cured, burn the benumbed limb itself with cauterizations proportionate to its bigness or smallness. Let the cauterization somewhat penetrate the thickness of the skin; then dress with ointments till healed.	0.88420033
Then treat it with the ointment until it heals. Some numbness that occurs in the hand and foot may be cauterized in the vertebrae of the back at the exit of the nerve that moves that limb, and the numbness will go away.	For numbness that occurs in the hand or foot it is possible to cauterize over the dorsal vertebrae at the exit of the nerve activating that part; and the numbness will go.	0.71813107
And no one should undertake this except one who is knowledgeable in the anatomy of the limbs and the exits of the nerves that move the body.	This should not be attempted except by one who has a good knowledge of the anatomy of the limbs and of the exits of the nerves that move the body.	0.87249315
